  "doc_id": "44110",
  "text": "When amputated, the caudal fin responds by rapidly sealing the wound with migrating epidermal cells, forming what is known as a wound epidermis or wound epithelia. Approximately 1 day post amputation (dpa), a blastema forms beneath the wound epidermis. By 2 dpa, outgrowth is seen in cells of the blastema and it is thought that proximal blastema cells differentiate to form lost tissue. This process of outgrowth and re-differentiation continues until the tissue is completely restored in approximately 2 weeks [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Much remains to be learned on what cell types contribute to the blastema and whether they are equivalent, multipotent cells or are a mixed population of cells restricted within a given cell lineage. Insight into blastema composition and function may ultimately allow experimental generation of a blastema in a mammalian model of limb regeneration.",
